{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6f1de0f7-4b33-444b-9d4f-13c2fcd518df","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01QbGuDHrNjVQraP363n6XjG","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating .NET 11 console app"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01LxGPwka7xYHN7rULBykypd","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null; dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Check available .NET SDK versions","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check available .NET SDK versions"}],"interactionId":"f332074b-b07c-4a30-8e6a-4a61293c2868","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants a .NET 11 console app that serializes a `Person` record to JSON with PascalCase property names using built-in framework features.\n\nIn .NET 9+, `System.Text.Json` added `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` as a built-in naming policy. Since the record has lowercase parameter names (`name`, `age`), C# will generate properties with those exact names. By default, `System.Text.Json` uses the property names as-is, so without a naming policy, the JSON would have `name` and `age` (lowercase). To get `Name` and `Age`, we need to set `PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase`.\n\n\nI need to clarify how C# positional records work—when you declare `public record Person(string name, int age)`, the compiler actually generates public properties that capitalize the first letter, so they become `Name` and `Age`, not lowercase. property name. Let me think again...\n\nActually, no. C# positional records use the EXACT parameter name as the property name. So `string name` becomes a property called `name`, not `Name`. This is a common gotcha.\n\nSo by default, `System.Text.Json` would serialize this as `{\"name\":\"...\",\"age\":...}` which is already lowercase. To get PascalCase (`Name`, `Age`), we need `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase`.\n\nWait, I need to double-check. In C#, `public record Person(string name, int age);` - the generated properties are actually `name` and `age` with lowercase first letters? Let me think carefully...\n\nActually, I just recalled: C# positional records generate properties with the EXACT same name as the constructor parameter. So if you write `string name`, the property is `name` (lowercase). The convention is to use PascalCase for parameters in records (like `string Name`), but the user explicitly used lowercase.\n\nSo with `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase`, the lowercase property names `name` and `age` would be converted to `Name` and `Age` in the JSON output. Now I'm trying to recall when `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` was introduced. I know `CamelCase` was available in .NET 6 and 7, but I'm uncertain about the exact version when `PascalCase` was added—it might have been .NET 8 or later. The user wants to use a built-in naming policy rather than create a custom one, so I'm assuming `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` exists in .NET 11 even if I'm not certain about its exact availability. Let me create a test project to verify this works.\n\nCreating a console app...","outputTokens":1379,"requestId":"EC08:17D0EF:C2A5B1:E2A87F:69FE84FB"},"id":"853f9199-763d-44ed-a72a-a33d38a5700d","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:38.224Z","parentId":"6f9a0a6d-c45d-412e-aff8-e73f527202b9"}
